The PDF/A standard defines provisions for long term archiving of electronic documents in the PDF format. All content in a PDF/A file must be contained in such a way that viewing or printing of the file can be achieved reliably over a long period of time.
PDF/A-1a is suitable for archiving PDF 1.3 or PDF 1.4 files whose content structure is accessible through structure tags.
PDF/A-1b is suitable for archiving PDF 1.3 or PDF 1.4 files whose content stucture is not accessible.
PDF/A-2a is suitable for archiving PDF files up to version 1.7 whose content structure is accessible through structure tags.
PDF/A-2b is suitable for archiving PDF files up to version 1.7 whose content structure is not accessible and whose text cannot be mapped to Unicode.
PDF/A-2u is suitable for archiving PDF files up to version 1.7 whose content structure is not accessible but whose text can be mapped to Unicode.

The PDF/E standard defines provisions for the use and exchange of engineering documents in the PDF format. It allows for the inclusion of dynamic content, like 3D models as well as a range of annotations, and at the same time requires the presence of all content and resources in the PDF file to guarantee reliable viewing and printing.

PDF/E-1 requires that all page content and resources neccessary for displaying or printing the document are included in the PDF file. A PDF/E file may be password protected and also supports the use of digital signatures.
The PDF/X standard defines provisions for reliable PDF exchange in the graphic arts industry. PDF/X files must contain all page content and resources for predictable viewing and ouput.
